text: What we seek is not small but big‚Äîa vision of spiritual over material development, collaboration over competition, connectedness over isolation, conservation over consumption and shared power over individual power.
In the end, brothers and sisters, remember this: it is not just about WHAT we fight for, it is about HOW we fight for it.
Third, let‚Äôs change the way we think about politics and elected office.
Second, let‚Äôs reject the false dichotomies that even some in our own party continue to put forward.
How? First, as Dr. King said, we must speak the inner truth that demands its real expression at this moment.
It is on US to take back our country, to re-form it as a true government by, for and of the people.

But make no mistake, the road ahead of us is long. Trump and his enabling Republicans destroy institutions from the FBI to the courts, from the EPA to the Media‚Äîand this is deeply, deeply dangerous.
Last year, we saw just that. From fighting back against the #MuslimBan, to defeating #TrumpCare, to the #MeToo movement, people have been making their voices heard.

But if Trump has done one thing, it is that he has made it abundantly clear to us that we have to awaken and stay woke as my good friend @BLeeForCongress will say. We can‚Äôt just fight for some of us, we have to fight for all of us.  And we have to be BOLD.
If the 2016 election taught us anything, it is that the consequences of apathy and voter distrust are severe.  Democracy can never be simply assumed‚Äîit has to be preserved, protected and advanced.

I like to say that I am not a woman on Monday, an immigrant on Tuesday, a worker on Wednesday and a mom on Thursday, I am all of those things all of the time and we must fight for all of those things all of the time.
You see, what I realized early on in my organizing career is that our problems lie partly in our tendency to silo issues.
I'm also proud to have been one of the partners with the @NAACP and @ACLU to demand police accountability, and to have fought with and for women‚Äôs rights across the board.

Nothing came easy‚Äîbut I am so proud to have served on the committee to pass the $15 minimum wage in Seattle, to have worked to pass marriage equality, to have helped lead the biggest anti-war march in Seattle against the Iraq war.
But needing economic power too, and that the only way to win was to build strong coalitions with workers, with labor, with the LGBTQ movement.
We recognized that we needed to wield political power too‚Äîso we ran the largest voter registration drive in the history of our state, registering over 23,000 new immigrants to vote.

Speak I did, and it led to an incredible 12 years of working with many of the folks in this room at #AVSummit18 to found and grow what became the largest immigrant advocacy organization in our state, organizing tens of thousands of immigrants
As Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.said: of course there is uncertainty, ‚ÄúBut We Must Speak‚Äù. Whatever the agony, whatever the risk, We Must Speak.
Individuals from 25 Arab and Muslim countries were being forced to be registered and fingerprinted, when thousands were being detained and questioned and deported.
In that particular post-9/11 moment when the patriotic pitch was peaking, when the beginnings of the first Muslim ban was being instituted, then called Special Registration.
I wasn‚Äôt intending to found anything but within a week of 9/11, I realized that everything had changed for people who looked like me.
I became an organizer after a decade of working on global health and justice issues because of September 11, 2001. Many of us organizers get called to the work completely unexpectedly.
I‚Äôm also very proud to be one of the very few ORGANIZERS in Congress!
It is such an honor to be in this room at #AVSummit18 with some of the true leaders and champions of building progressive momentum to take back our country!
